div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 206px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;
div.div:
IT Developer creates collect, Standards, Config, and RBACPermission plugins that become cabailities that Servers can have.
This role does not need access to production servers.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 271px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;
div.div: The more traditional Sys admin role has access to configure production servers but does only needs access to activated/deactivate capabilities, not unrestrictricted configuration

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 266px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal;
div.div:
Creating Server configurations is turned into an activitiy similar to software development where an SDLC determines the outcome and no access to production servers is needed.
Production sysadmin becomes a less priviledged activity that has control of how resources are provisioned but does not have the permission to create new configuration types.
